Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry
all produce.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @shallot{1}. Thinly slice @celery{2.5%ounce}
crosswise. Strip @thyme{¼%ounce}(minced) leaves from stems; mince leaves until
you have 1 tsp. Dice @demi-baguette{1} into ½-inch pieces.

In a #small bowl{}, combine half the @chicken stock concentrate{2} (you'll
use the rest later) and @water{¼%cup}.

> 4 SERVINGS: Mince thyme leaves until you have 2 tsp. Use ½ cup water.

Pat @pork chops{12%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with
@salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon} in a #medium pan{} over medium-high
heat. Add pork and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes} per
side.

Remove pan from heat. Transfer pork to a #cutting board{} to rest.

While pork cooks, toss @green beans{6%ounce} on a #baking sheet{} with a
drizzle of olive oil, salt, and pepper.

Roast on middle rack until browned and tender, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat @butter{3%tablespoon} and a drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon}
in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add diced baguette; toast, stirring,
until golden brown and crisp, ~{5-7%minutes}. Transfer to a #plate{}. Wipe
out pan.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{4%teaspoon} in same pan over medium-high heat.
Add shallot and celery; cook until tender, ~{3-5%minutes}. Season with salt and
pepper. Add minced thyme and baguette. Stir in stock mixture until absorbed,
~{1-2%minutes}. Turn off heat; cover to keep warm.

> TIP: Prefer a softer stuffing? Add a splash more water after stirring in the
> stock mixture.

Heat pan used for pork over medium-high heat. Add @fig jam{2%tablespoon},
@water{¼%cup}, and remaining stock concentrates. Bring to a boil and cook,
stirring occasionally, until reduced, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Remove from heat; stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} until melted. Season with salt
and pepper.

Thinly slice pork crosswise.

Divide pork, green beans, and stuffing between #plates{}. Spoon pan sauce over
pork and serve.